# Copy to /opt/solinteg/solinteg.env and fill in. Loaded by both systemd units.
# chmod 600 — it holds secrets.
#
# IMPORTANT: this is a plain KEY=VALUE file read by systemd's EnvironmentFile= directive,
# which does NOT support inline "# comment" text after a value — it becomes part of the
# value verbatim (confirmed 2026-07-10 on-device: `X=98   # comment` is parsed as
# X="98   # comment", which a Python float()/int() cast on the other end crashes on). Every
# comment below is on its own line, never after a value, for exactly this reason — keep that
# convention if you add more.

# ── Inverter Modbus connection (poller + controller) ──
# 192.168.1.50 below is a placeholder for the simple case: inverter on your home LAN with a
# DHCP reservation. The reference deployment instead runs the inverter on its own isolated
# subnet (192.168.99.2) with no direct LAN exposure — Modbus TCP has no auth, so anything on
# the same network segment as the inverter can command it. See deploy/README.md §13 and
# deploy/network-isolation/ if you want that same isolation; it's optional but recommended.
# Set a DHCP reservation for the inverter's IP either way.
SOLINTEG_HOST=192.168.1.50
SOLINTEG_PORT=502
# Dongle forwards to RTU slave 255 (0xFF), NOT 1 — see MODBUS.md.
SOLINTEG_SLAVE_ID=255
POLL_INTERVAL=30

# ── Inverter control safety gates (see inverter_control.py / MODBUS.md) ──
# ARMED is deliberately NOT set here: every register write is a no-op until you
# explicitly export SOLINTEG_CONTROL_ARMED=1 for the process that should write.
#SOLINTEG_CONTROL_ARMED=1
# Confirmed on-device 2026-07-02 by scripts/tools/probe_50207_sign.py.
SOLINTEG_50207_SIGN=neg_charge
# The five below are read by BOTH the Python control scripts AND the web app (lib/constants.ts)
# — one shared value per hardware fact, not per-language copies. Since 2026-07-10.
# Also written to inverter regs 52502/52503 (native protection).
SOLINTEG_SOC_FLOOR_PCT=8
# Enforced in inverter_control.py; the DP optimizer doesn't model it (see lib/constants.ts).
SOLINTEG_SOC_CEILING_PCT=98
# Hardware charge/discharge limit — clamped before any write.
#SOLINTEG_BATTERY_MAX_W=15360
# Your fuse rating's power cap — the one most other installs differ on.
#SOLINTEG_GRID_CAP_W=11000
# Usable capacity, kWh.
#SOLINTEG_BATTERY_KWH=25.6
# Round-trip efficiency (datasheet value).
#SOLINTEG_BATTERY_RT_EFF=0.96

# ── Shared data file: poller writes it, the web app reads it ──
INVERTER_DATA_PATH=/opt/solinteg/live.json

# ── Telemetry time-series (SQLite). Inverter poller appends readings; web app appends
#    price curves + optimizer runs; weather poller appends irradiance/temp/wind.
#    All write the same file (WAL mode). Web-app telemetry is OFF unless this is set. ──
TELEMETRY_DB_PATH=/opt/solinteg/telemetry.db

# ── Ecowitt weather station (cloud API v3). Powers the solar-forecast calibration.
#    Keys from ecowitt.net → user profile → API keys. ──
ECOWITT_APPLICATION_KEY=your_application_key
ECOWITT_API_KEY=your_api_key
# Your station's MAC, from ecowitt.net device list.
ECOWITT_MAC=AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF
WEATHER_POLL_INTERVAL=60

# ── Pricing / site config (web app; see lib/constants.ts). All optional — most defaults below
#    are the reference deployment's own measured contract terms (surcharge, VAT, skatt, export
#    bonus); GPS coordinates and battery replacement cost are illustrative placeholders, not
#    that installation's real numbers. Override all of these for your own contract/site;
#    PRICE_ZONE is the one most other Swedish (SE1-SE4) adopters would actually need to change.
#
#    IMPORTANT — unlike SOLINTEG_HOST/TELEMETRY_DB_PATH etc., changing one of THESE and just
#    restarting solinteg-web is NOT enough: fetchPrices()/fetchSolarForecast() use Next's
#    'use cache' + Partial Prerendering, so their result gets baked into the build output at
#    `npm run build` time, not read fresh per-request. deploy/to-nuc.sh's remote build step
#    now sources this file before building (2026-07-10 fix — it didn't before, so a build could
#    silently use stale/default values even though the running service had the override) so a
#    normal redeploy picks these up correctly; it only bites if you edit this file directly on
#    the NUC and just `systemctl restart solinteg-web` without rebuilding. ──
# SE1, SE2, SE3, or SE4 — falls back to SE3 if unset/invalid.
#PRICE_ZONE=SE3
# Your supplier's own påslag+elcertifikat, öre/kWh.
#SUPPLIER_SURCHARGE_ORE=11.5
# Your grid company's nätnytta export compensation, öre/kWh.
#EXPORT_BONUS_ORE=5.10
# Flat energiskatt + överföringsavgift, öre/kWh (buy-side only).
#SKATT_OVERFORING_ORE=71
# Moms on the energy price.
#VAT_RATE=0.25
# Decimal degrees — feeds the solar/weather forecast APIs.
#SITE_LATITUDE=57.64
#SITE_LONGITUDE=11.78
# What you paid for inverter+battery — feeds the wear-cost model.
#BATTERY_REPLACEMENT_COST_SEK=60000

# ── Web app ──
# LAN-only deployment: no Clerk / no auth. The dashboard is open on the local network.

# ── Alerting (solinteg-watchdog.timer / solinteg-healthcheck.timer). See deploy/README.md
#    for the ntfy app + healthchecks.io setup steps (both are one-time, done in their own
#    apps/websites, not here). ──
NTFY_SERVER=https://ntfy.sh
# Pick a long random topic name — on the public ntfy.sh instance, anyone who knows/guesses
# it can read your alerts. Generate one with:
#   python -c "import secrets,base64; print('solinteg-' + base64.b32encode(secrets.token_bytes(15)).decode().rstrip('=').lower())"
NTFY_TOPIC=

# Optional: a healthchecks.io "ping URL" (free tier). Pinged every 10 min by
# solinteg-heartbeat-ping.timer; healthchecks.io itself alerts (via its own ntfy/email/
# webhook integration) if the ping ever stops arriving — the one failure mode nothing
# running ON the NUC can detect (the NUC being fully off). Leave blank to skip this layer.
#HEALTHCHECKS_PING_URL=https://hc-ping.com/your-uuid-here

# Optional tuning for the alerting layer — sane defaults, only touch after checking real
# behaviour (query control_actions/readings for the actual timing/staleness distribution):
#WATCHDOG_STALE_S=240
#WATCHDOG_ALERT_COOLDOWN_S=1800
#POLLER_STALE_S=300
#WEATHER_STALE_S=1800
#CONTROL_ERROR_WINDOW_S=900
#HEALTHCHECK_ALERT_COOLDOWN_S=14400
#DISPATCH_SOC_DIVERGENCE_KWH=3.0

# Replan triggers (see dispatch_loop.py's module docstring, "REPLAN TRIGGERS" section): lets
# the dispatch loop ask the web app to compute a fresh plan on drift/guard/missing-plan
# conditions instead of only ever picking one up from the next timer-driven render (see
# deploy/solinteg-telemetry.timer). "0" = off (kill switch, reverts to the pre-feature
# timer-only cadence); "1" = on (default); "shadow" = compute the same decision and log it,
# but never actually call out — use this to watch trigger frequency in journalctl before
# letting it touch the web app.
#DISPATCH_REPLAN_TRIGGERS=1
# Preemptive SoC-drift threshold (kWh) for requesting a replan — deliberately HALF of
# DISPATCH_SOC_DIVERGENCE_KWH's own default above, so a fresh, live-anchored plan usually
# already exists by the time drift would otherwise cross that guard's own wider threshold.
#DISPATCH_REPLAN_DRIFT_KWH=1.5
# Floor between replan requests, regardless of which (or how many) trigger conditions fired
# in that window — coalesces bursty triggers behind one request instead of one each.
#DISPATCH_REPLAN_DEBOUNCE_S=120
# Where to POST the replan request — the web app runs on the same NUC by default.
#DISPATCH_REPLAN_URL=http://localhost:3000/api/replan
#DISPATCH_SOLAR_SHORTFALL_KWH=0.5
#DISK_FREE_MIN_PCT=10
#BACKUP_KEEP=21

# ── Offsite backup mirror (scripts/services/backup_offsite.py / solinteg-backup-offsite.timer).
#    Local nightly backups only protect against DB corruption or a bad deploy, not a dead disk
#    or a dead NUC — this mirrors BACKUP_DIR to a cloud remote via rclone. Requires `rclone`
#    installed (apt install rclone) — see deploy/README.md §12d. Leave RCLONE_OFFSITE_DEST blank
#    to skip this layer entirely (the local-only backup still runs). No rclone config file is
#    used; credentials are supplied via RCLONE_CONFIG_<REMOTE>_* env vars below, matching the
#    remote name in RCLONE_OFFSITE_DEST. Example below is for Backblaze B2 (free tier, 10 GB) —
#    swap the RCLONE_CONFIG_B2_* values and remote name for a different backend if preferred. ──
#RCLONE_OFFSITE_DEST=b2:your-bucket-name
#RCLONE_CONFIG_B2_TYPE=b2
#RCLONE_CONFIG_B2_ACCOUNT=your_application_key_id
#RCLONE_CONFIG_B2_KEY=your_application_key
